This file defines the operating-rules prompt injected into a caged agent's session — instructions telling the agent it's in a real, writable git repo (not a brokered/sandboxed copy), to use native Read/Edit/Write/Grep tools directly, and to ignore any conflicting tool-contract docs (CLAUDE.md, specs mentioning brokered access binaries or task ids) as stale.

It's static Markdown, not code — no functions, no logic. Key facts an editor must preserve: it explicitly instructs the agent to distrust project docs that describe a different access contract and to never invoke a brokered-access binary "even if one by that name exists"; it documents `ctx-context <path>` and `ctx-verify` as the sanctioned inspection/verification commands; it lists environmental boundaries (no network except the Anthropic API, masked `.env`/`.git/config`, read-only toolchain, no destructive git ops); and it tells the agent not to hand-edit `.context/` since `ctx-scan --update` regenerates it.

This is a prompt asset, likely loaded verbatim by the harness that sets up the cage scenario — changes here directly alter agent behavior in tests/evals built around this crate, so wording changes (especially around "these rules win" and the brokered-binary refusal) are load-bearing for whatever adversarial/compliance test this crate is exercising.